                header(class="text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-proxima-bold") Television and the power of shared experience
                p Try for a moment to recall a time when you saw a movie in a  theater.
                img(loading="lazy" src="media/shamann-walton/walton-circle-image@802.png" srcset="media/shamann-walton/walton-circle-image@600.png 600w, media/shamann-walton/walton-circle-image@802.png 802w, media/shamann-walton/walton-circle-image@1200.png 1200w, media/shamann-walton/walton-circle-image@1600.png 1600w" id="walton-circle-image" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 85vw, (max-width:1024px) 90vw, 802px" class="border-5 lg:border-8 border-current text-violet-100 rounded-full shadow-2xl float-right shape-outside -mr-32 xs:-mr-48 sm:-mr-56 lg:-mr-64 scale-95 " width="802" height="802" style="max-width: 802px !important; ")
                p When we're seeing a movie in a sold-out theater, we  have a very different experience than when we watch it alone  at home, on our favorite couch.
                p When we collectively experience the same emotion as  everyone else around us, that experience is indelible. Sports matches, rock concerts, solar eclipses, Princess Diana's  funeral, these are the defining moments of our lives. Where  were you when the second plane struck?
                p Meanwhile, a 30-second Super Bowl commercial costs $7 million because nothing else delivers an audience of 100  million viewers, instantly catapulting the brand into the national discourse for weeks to come. What a bargain.
                p When a brand is advertised on television, it appears alongside  other brands that are also advertised on television - brands  like Pepsi or Toyota.
                p When a brand is advertised only on mobile screens, it shares  that screen with today's equivalents of snake oil.
                p In recent years, when Facebook, Uber, AirBnb have had an  important announcement, they have chosen to buy full page  ads in traditional newspapers like the Wall Street Journal or the New York Times. These marketers are “digital-native  companies.” Indeed, some could not have existed before the  advent of smartphones.
                p They are capable of delivering their message to every  individual in their target audience through a push notification on their own apps.
                p Then why print the message on dead trees?
                p Because a full-page newspaper ad brings a gravity, a self assurance, and a respectability that an online banner ad  cannot.
                p In the 2020s, cinema, radio, outdoor and TV  continue to retain their place in the media mix. New digital  options add to the media planner's toolkit, but rarely replace  existing channels.
                p Can anyone name a medium that was once dominant, but no  longer exists? Even the poster is still around.
